            "last_activity_date": 1427088003,
            "creation_date": 1427088003,
            "body": "<p>Your abstract static method would serve no purpose. Since static methods need to be called directly on the class that defines them, there is no layer of indirection that would be served by them being abstract in a base class.<\/p>\n\n<p>In essence, since you have already identified that you need to call eg. <code>RectangleTool.getCursor()<\/code> or <code>EllipseTool.getCursor()<\/code>, the existence of a <code>Tool.getCursor()<\/code> makes no difference, as no part of the code can refer directly to it anyway.<\/p>\n\n<p>It would be a different thing, of course, if Java supported polymorphism for static methods, but it doesn't.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 29203722,
            "question_id": 29203579
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f93fabe952813d5f0373aba06202b990?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 251102,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 528246,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/528246/nicholas-daley-okoye",
                "reputation": 2447,
                "display_name": "Nicholas Daley-Okoye"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1427088347,
            "creation_date": 1427088347,
            "body": "<p>I would suggest that it may be better design to give up on wanting static methods here.<br>\nUsing static methods on your tools isn't going to be possible without using reflection to call them.\nBut, beyond that restricting yourself in this way might remove the future possibility of writing parameterised tools, or of reusing code between tools.  I don't know the full scope of your situation, but imagine something like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Tool pentagonTool = ShapeTools.regularPolygonWithEdges(5);\nTool triangleTool = ShapeTools.regularPolygonWithEdges(3);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I would suggest that you get rid of your requirement for static methods, and for the tool implementations where it is only methods, make those implementations singletons.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Tool tool1 = RectangleTool.INSTANCE.getCursor();\nList&lt;Tool&gt; toolbox = ImmutableList.of(\n    RectangleTool.INSTANCE,\n    EllipseTool.INSTANCE,\n    SquareTool.INSTANCE,\n    CircleTool.INSTANCE\n);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 29203778,
            "question_id": 29203579
        }
    ],
